# Demo Conventions

## Repository Purpose

This is a multi-cloud (Azure + AWS) demo for multi-cluster application distribution using ACM, Submariner, and Service Mesh, built as a Red Hat Scholars courseware site using AsciiDoc and Antora. It must never contain customer or user names.

## Structure

- `documentation/` contains all AsciiDoc courseware content (Antora component)
- `documentation/modules/ROOT/pages/` contains the course pages in `.adoc` format
- YAML manifests live in the root step directories and are referenced directly from the AsciiDoc pages
- `00-current-state/` simulates the current manual deployment problem (step zero)
- `01-acm-workload-placement/` solves placement with ACM + OpenShift GitOps (ApplicationSet push model)
- `kustomize/` contains base + overlays for the demo-app workload manifests (the ApplicationSet source path)
- `02-submariner-connectivity/` deploys Submariner via ACM for encrypted cross-cloud (AWS to Azure) L3 connectivity
- `03-service-mesh-traffic-management/` adds Service Mesh for networking and failover
- `setup/` contains Terraform + post-install script for provisioning clusters (internal, not part of the demo)
- Steps are progressive: each builds on the previous one

## AsciiDoc Formatting

- Every numbered step must have a *What* and *Why* pair in bold:
  ```
  *What:* One sentence describing the concrete action.

  *Why:* One sentence explaining why this step matters.
  ```
- Every step must have a collapsible verification block:
  ```
  .Verify: Description of what to check
  [%collapsible]
  ====
  ...commands and expected output...
  ====
  ```
- Use `[.console-input]` before source blocks for copy-pasteable commands
- Use `[.console-output]` before source blocks showing expected output
- Reference YAML manifests by file path in `oc apply -f` commands (no inline includes)
- Do not use em dashes. Use regular dashes (`-`) instead
- Use `'''` for horizontal rules between steps
- Cross-reference other pages with `xref:page.adoc[Label]`
- External links use `link:URL[Label]`
- Use `NOTE:`, `TIP:`, `IMPORTANT:`, `WARNING:` admonitions
- All doc links must point to `docs.redhat.com` or `docs.openshift.com`, no placeholders
- Use attributes from `_attributes.adoc` for version numbers (e.g. `{ocp-version}`, `{acm-version}`)

## CLI Conventions

- Every `oc` command in the AsciiDoc pages must include an explicit `--context` flag (`hub`, `cluster-a`, or `cluster-b`)
- Never use `oc login` inside step pages; context setup is done once in `00-setup.adoc`
- Hub-targeted commands use `--context hub`; managed cluster commands use `--context cluster-a` or `--context cluster-b`
- YAML files that contain `${VARIABLE}` placeholders must be applied via `envsubst < file.yaml | oc apply --context <ctx> -f -`
- All workshop variables are exported once in `00-setup.adoc`; YAML files reference them via `${VAR}` syntax

## Content Rules

- Never include customer names, user names, or email addresses anywhere in the repository
- All content must be in English
- Prefer `registry.access.redhat.com` or `registry.redhat.io` images over Docker Hub
- Use Red Hat / OpenShift-native components when they cover the use case (ACM, Service Mesh, GitOps, etc.)
- Mention Red Hat products because they fit the solution, not to promote them

## YAML Conventions

- Every YAML file starts with a comment block: filename and purpose
- Use `app.kubernetes.io/part-of: demo-app` label consistently
- Include resource requests and limits on Deployments
- Include readiness and liveness probes where applicable
- YAML files live in the step directories (e.g. `00-current-state/`) and `kustomize/` and are referenced directly from the AsciiDoc pages
